{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 11 "factor (H);" }}{PARA 11 "" 
1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*&,&%\"xG\"\"\"\"\"#F&F&,&*&F'F&F%F&F&F&!\"\"F&" }
}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 650 "In tho
se cases where Maple did not find enough linear factors, there is a re
ason why Maple did not.  Maple makes an assumption that if the coeffic
ients of a polynomial are all given exactly (as integers or rational n
umbers [ratios of integer]), then you are only interested in finding e
xact factors (factors where the coefficients are integers or rational \+
numbers).  The Fundamental Theorem of Algebra doesn't guarantee that t
he factors of  a polynomial will necessarily have the same kind of coe
fficients as the polynomial, only the polynomial can be factored.  You
 can force Maple to report additional (approximate) factors.  For exam
ple,  compare:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 
0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 10 "factor(h);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*&
,&%\"xG\"\"\"F&F&F&,&*$)F%\"\"#F&F&\"\"&!\"\"F&" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> \+
" 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 18 "factor(h,sqrt(5));" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" 
{XPPMATH 20 "6#*(,&%\"xG\"\"\"*$\"\"&#F&\"\"#!\"\"F&,&F%F&F'F&F&,&F%F&
F&F&F&" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
52 "What is the difference?  The extra-term is called a " }{TEXT 274 
18 "field extension.  " }{TEXT -1 178 "Adding it tells Maple to consid
er additonal factors where the coefficients are allowed to include ele
ments from the field extension.  It is fairly clear from the factorizt
ion of " }{TEXT 275 1 "h" }{TEXT -1 280 " all by itself that something
 involving  sqrt(5)  would have to be included.  However, there are pr
oblems where there is not a obvious clue as to which specific field ex
tension should be added.  If you are willing to accept an appropriate \+
solution, then using the field extension " }{TEXT 276 4 "real" }{TEXT 
-1 179 " tells Maple to factor the polynomial using a floating point a
pproximation scheme.  For example, consider (here I am pretending I do
n't see that adding  sqrt(5) would be optimal):" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 10 "factor(h);" 
}}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*&,&%\"xG\"\"\"F&F&F&,&*$)F%\"\"#F&F
&\"\"&!\"\"F&" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 15 "factor(h,r
eal);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*(,&%\"xG\"\"\"$\"+xz1OA!\"*F
&F&,&F%F&$F&\"\"!F&F&,&F%F&$\"+xz1OAF)!\"\"F&" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 91 "Finally, the Fundamental \+
Theorem of Algebra does not guarantee that a polynomial of degree " }
{TEXT 277 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 11 " will have " }{TEXT 278 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 
53 " real linear factors.  Rather, only hat it will have " }{TEXT 279 
1 "n" }{TEXT -1 134 " linear factors.  What is the difference?  Some o
f the factors may involve complex roots rather than real roots.  For e
xample compare:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> \+
" 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 10 "factor(F);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#
*(,&%\"xG\"\"\"F&!\"\"F&,&F%F&F&F&F&,&*$)F%\"\"#F&F&F&F&F&" }}}{EXCHG 
